column3: Description
A unique identifier for the mortgage loan.
The most recent month and year available for the mortgage or the disposition date of the mortgage.
A code indicating the reason the loan's balance was reduced to zero or experienced a credit event, if applicable.
column4:
C = Mortgage In Progress
P = Prepaid or Matured
T =  Third Party Sale
S = Short Sale
R = Repurchased
F = Deed-in-Lieu; REO Disposition
N = Notes Sales
L = Reperforming Loan Sale
D = Deliquent

column3: The origination channel used by the party that delivered the loan to the issuer.
column4: Retail = R; Correspondent = C; Broker = B

column3: The name of the entity that delivered the mortgage loan.
column4: For sellers that represent less than one percent of volume within a given acquisition quarter as represented by the original unpaid principal balance, "Other" will be displayed in this field.

column3: The name of the entity that serves as the primary servicer of the mortgage loan.
column4: For activity periods prior to December 2001, Servicer Name will be blank since the servicer information for this period is unavailable.

column3: The original interest rate on a mortgage loan as identified in the original mortgage note.
The rate of interest in effect for the most recent periodic installment due.
column4: For a mortgage loan that has been modified, this value will be updated to reflect the modified terms, if applicable.

column3: The dollar amount of the loan as stated on the note at the time the loan was originated.
The original value of the property.
The current actual outstanding unpaid principal balance of a mortgage loan, reflective of payments actually received from the related borrower.
column4: Due to borrower privacy considerations, this value will be masked for the first six months of the life of the loan.

column3: For fixed-rate, adjustable-rate and Interest-only mortgages, the number of months in which regularly scheduled borrower payments are due at the time the loan was originated.
The origination date of each mortgage.
The date of the first scheduled mortgage loan payment to be made by the borrower under the terms of the mortgage loan documents.
The ratio, expressed as a percentage, obtained by dividing the amount of the loan at origination by the value of the property.

column2: Original Combined Loan to Value Ratio (CLTV)
column3: The ratio, expressed as a percentage, obtained by dividing the amount of all known outstanding loans at origination by the value of the property.
The number of individuals obligated to repay the mortgage loan.
The ratio obtained by dividing the total monthly debt expense by the total monthly income of the borrower at the time the loan was originated.
column4: For values outside the allowable range, or if unknown, this value will be blank.

column3: A numerical value used by the financial services industry to evaluate the quality of borrower credit. Credit scores are typically based on a proprietary statistical model that is developed for use by credit data repositories. These credit repositories apply the model to borrower credit information to arrive at a credit score.
column4: Represents the credit score provided by the Seller at the time of loan acquisition.  If the borrower credit score is unknown, the value will be blank.

column3: A numerical value used by the financial services industry to evaluate the quality of borrower credit. Credit scores are typically based on a proprietary statistical model that is developed for use by credit data repositories. These credit repositories apply the model to co-borrower credit information to arrive at a credit score.
column4: Represents the credit score provided by the Seller at the time of loan acquisition. If the co-borrower credit score  is not applicable or unknown, the value will be blank.

column3: An indicator that denotes if the borrower or co-borrower qualifies as a first-time homebuyer.
column4:
An individual is to be considered a first-time homebuyer who (1) is purchasing the property; (2) will reside in the property; and (3) had no ownership interest (sole or joint) in a residential property during the three-year period preceding the date of the purchase of the property. In addition, an individual who is a displaced homemaker or single parent also will be considered a first-time homebuyer if he or she had no ownership interest in a principal residence (other than a joint ownership interest with a spouse) during the preceding three-year time period.

Y = Yes
N= No
Null = Unknown

column3: An indicator that denotes whether the mortgage loan is either a refinance mortgage or a purchase money mortgage. Purpose may be the purchase of a new property or refinance of an existing lien (with cash out or with no cash out).
column4:
Cash-Out Refinance = C
Refinance = R
Purchase = P
Refinance-Not Specified = U

column3: An indicator that denotes whether the property type secured by the mortgage loan is a condominium, co-operative, planned urban development (PUD), manufactured home, or single-family home.
column4:
CO = condominium
CP = co-operative
PU = Planned Urban Development
MH = manufactured home
SF = single-family home

column3: The number of units comprising the related mortgaged property (one, two, three, or four).
The classification describing the property occupancy status at the time the loan was originated.
column4: Principal = P; Second = S; Investor = I; Unknown = U

column3: A two-letter abbreviation indicating the state or territory within which the property securing the mortgage loan is located.

The numeric Metropolitan Statistical Area Code for the property securing the mortgage loan. MSAs are established by the US Office of Management and Budget. An area usually qualifies as an MSA if it is defined by the Bureau of the Census as an urbanized area and has a population of 50,000 or more in a total metropolitan area of at least 100,000. An MSA may consist of one or more counties.
column4: If the property is not in a designated MSA, the value will default to “00000.”

column3: Limited to the first three digits of the code designated by the U.S. Postal Service where the subject property is located.

The original percentage of mortgage insurance coverage obtained for an insured conventional mortgage loan and used following the occurrence of an event of default to calculate the insurance benefit, as defined by the underlying master primary insurance policy.
The date in which the mortgage first became 30 days delinquent. Only implies they missed a payment, not necessarily a forclosure.

column3: The unpaid principal balance of the loan at the time of 90 days delinquency. Only implies they missed a payment, not necessarily a forclosure.

The due date of the last paid installment that was collected for the mortgage loan.
The date on which the completion of the legal action of foreclosure occurred.
The cumulative net realized gain or loss amounts for a mortgage loan resulting from a credit event.
column4: Determination of a credit event is defined in each of the individual CRT offering documents. A positive value indicates a net realized loss, and a negative value indicates a net realized gain. If the cumulative credit event net gain or loss is not applicable, the value will be blank.  This field will be populated based on the individual deal claims and reporting timeline after the disclosed Disposition Date of the mortgage loan or the subject property.

column3: An indicator that denotes whether or not the type of mortgage loan is a relocation mortgage loan, made to borrowers whose employers relocate their employees.
